I expected more from this one, but instead it was... a slightly better than average Bond flick? Nothing revelatory, but a fun enough romp. This felt like what it was: Bond adapted into a 90s franchise film, complete with someone questionable special effects and a couple of metacommentary moments on the older films that mostly fall flat.Trevelyan is the best Bond villain concept we've had in a while (except perhaps Benicio del Toro giving us a nice honeymoooonnn?) but…

It's been a while since I've checked in with James Bond, but my main memory of The Living Daylights is that the post-Moore franchise couldn't figure out to do with a younger Bond. Watching License to Kill feels like a doubling down on the uncertainty. There's a lot going on here, but you can feel the overall studio note being "bigger! more!"Sometimes it works (delightful to see Q try his hand at some field work), sometimes it doesn't (Live…

Drags a bit in the back half in the "slides from a 5 star movie to a 4 star movie" sense. I had a big ol' smile on my face for all the happy parts of the movie and the emotional punches all landed. So fun!

The Farleigh sex scene is framed and lit exactly the same as the Frank-N-Furter sex scenes from The Rocky Horror Picture Show and it was entirely impossible for me to take the last hour of this movie seriously for this reason alone.
Slightly-better-than-average Pixar for me (of recent Pixars I'll take Luca or Turning Red over this). Visually beautiful and a good clip of funny jokes. A pleasant family movie night experience!

At some point (probably the part where the script stops adding moments of levity and starts deservedly swinging its dramatic sledgehammer) I stopped watching this as a holistic film and started watching the individual performances, which isn't something that happens to me a lot. An incredible show of acting craft from all of the leads.

I preferred the affiliated podcast from the Boston Globe on the same subject, but the documentary has a couple of things going for it (particularly greater participation from the Bennett family) that make it worth a watch as well.
